1
00:00:04,177 --> 00:00:09,820
Welcome. Thanks for coming out. I really appreciate it.

2
00:00:09,820 --> 00:00:14,102
So you're here to talk about, or to listen to me talk about Broken Age

3
00:00:14,102 --> 00:00:19,665
and the animation style and workflow.

4
00:00:19,665 --> 00:00:23,147
Let me start off by telling you a little bit about Broken Age.

5
00:00:23,147 --> 00:00:27,029
If you haven't played the game, it's a point-and-click adventure game.

6
00:00:27,029 --> 00:00:31,812
It's a story that deals with a young boy who is trying to find his own independence.

7
00:00:32,300 --> 00:00:36,161
and about a girl who is trying to save her village.

8
00:00:36,161 --> 00:00:40,041
The way that I'll proceed is I will talk a little bit

9
00:00:40,041 --> 00:00:42,322
about my own background, just briefly,

10
00:00:42,322 --> 00:00:45,402
and then I'll go into the inspirations

11
00:00:45,402 --> 00:00:47,243
of the Broken Age animation style,

12
00:00:47,243 --> 00:00:49,523
and then I'll go into sort of the nuts and bolts

13
00:00:49,523 --> 00:00:52,724
of how we did it, and I'll try to leave

14
00:00:52,724 --> 00:00:54,944
a little bit of time at the end for some Q&A

15
00:00:54,944 --> 00:00:56,385
if anybody has any questions.

16
00:00:56,385 --> 00:01:01,826
So I have been in the industry for 14 years.

17
00:01:02,822 --> 00:01:05,964
For 14 of those years I've been at Double Fine.

18
00:01:05,964 --> 00:01:08,806
So I have been there my entire career.

19
00:01:08,806 --> 00:01:15,410
I think in game developer years, that equals somewhere around 800 years, I would say.

20
00:01:15,410 --> 00:01:18,312
I'm the Yoda of the studio.

21
00:01:18,312 --> 00:01:24,476
The hair growing in my ears now and bald head, everything.

22
00:01:24,476 --> 00:01:27,077
In my time at Double Fine, I've...

23
00:01:27,525 --> 00:01:30,867
had several roles, primarily animation,

24
00:01:30,867 --> 00:01:34,029
but I've also done rigging and character modeling as well,

25
00:01:34,029 --> 00:01:37,011
which came in handy during the pre-production of this game.

26
00:01:37,011 --> 00:01:43,214
Just briefly, I worked on Psychonauts as an animator,

27
00:01:43,214 --> 00:01:46,436
Brutal Legend, Once Upon a Monster,

28
00:01:46,436 --> 00:01:48,717
I was the lead animator on that game,

29
00:01:48,717 --> 00:01:49,538
Costume Quest.

30
00:01:50,053 --> 00:01:52,414
Did some work on that, Middlemanager of Justice,

31
00:01:52,414 --> 00:01:56,296
which was the first time I'd done some 2D animation

32
00:01:56,296 --> 00:01:57,896
professionally.

33
00:01:57,896 --> 00:01:59,837
And then Autonomous, which I don't know,

34
00:01:59,837 --> 00:02:01,438
some of you may have heard of Autonomous.

35
00:02:01,438 --> 00:02:05,019
Worked on that with Lee Petty.

36
00:02:05,019 --> 00:02:07,960
And Hack and Slash was also 2D.

37
00:02:07,960 --> 00:02:11,481
So having that 2D and 3D experience

38
00:02:11,481 --> 00:02:15,023
actually came in handy with Broken Age.

39
00:02:15,023 --> 00:02:17,203
So let's go ahead and get started.

40
00:02:19,357 --> 00:02:24,218
In 2012, after a 13-year break from the point-and-click adventure game genre,

41
00:02:24,218 --> 00:02:29,799
Tim Schafer saw an opportunity through Kickstarter to return to that genre,

42
00:02:29,799 --> 00:02:34,540
and he ran a successful Kickstarter campaign, which you may have heard of,

43
00:02:34,540 --> 00:02:37,301
and the game that came out of that was Broken Age.

44
00:02:37,301 --> 00:02:43,042
Tim tapped me early on and asked me if I was interested in coming onto the team

45
00:02:43,042 --> 00:02:46,123
and lead the animation group and come up and develop.

46
00:02:46,614 --> 00:02:48,236
of the animation pipeline.

47
00:02:48,236 --> 00:02:50,538
Now I'd worked with Tim on two other games,

48
00:02:50,538 --> 00:02:53,140
Psychonauts and Brutal Legend,

49
00:02:53,140 --> 00:02:57,404
totaling almost 10 years of my life.

50
00:02:57,404 --> 00:03:00,206
Tim told me this would be a short game,

51
00:03:00,206 --> 00:03:01,908
probably one year long.

52
00:03:01,908 --> 00:03:05,150
So we are now three years.

53
00:03:05,150 --> 00:03:07,893
My relationship with Tim is I love him very much,

54
00:03:07,893 --> 00:03:10,515
but when it comes to working on his projects,

55
00:03:10,515 --> 00:03:11,836
I feel much like this woman.

56
00:03:17,362 --> 00:03:21,204
At the end of this ride, I'm sure she still loved her son,

57
00:03:21,204 --> 00:03:25,167
just like I loved him at the end of the projects.

58
00:03:25,167 --> 00:03:28,490
But they can be difficult and painful at times,

59
00:03:28,490 --> 00:03:30,271
but also very rewarding.

60
00:03:30,271 --> 00:03:31,993
So.

61
00:03:34,111 --> 00:03:38,934
Tim knew that he wanted the art of the game to be based off of Nathan Stapley's art style.

62
00:03:38,934 --> 00:03:42,717
Nathan had been at the studio for even longer than I had,

63
00:03:42,717 --> 00:03:45,498
and Tim had always really appreciated his work.

64
00:03:45,498 --> 00:03:48,240
And I was very familiar with it.

65
00:03:48,240 --> 00:03:52,763
These are actually three paintings that hang in my home that he did.

66
00:03:52,763 --> 00:03:56,485
So I was really excited to be able to come onto a game

67
00:03:56,485 --> 00:04:02,209
and actually develop an animation system where we'd be able to bring his style to life.

68
00:04:06,764 --> 00:04:13,953
Early on in the process, we had some studio artists, Lee Petty, who was the art director on the game,

69
00:04:13,953 --> 00:04:15,896
Scott Campbell, Nathan Stapley.

70
00:04:16,858 --> 00:04:20,421
Peter Chan, they were all doing just some character mock-ups.

71
00:04:20,421 --> 00:04:24,044
I was not on the project yet, but I was monitoring the forums.

72
00:04:24,044 --> 00:04:26,626
We have some internal forums and I was keeping an eye on those forums

73
00:04:26,626 --> 00:04:30,550
and just seeing what kind of styles they were coming up with

74
00:04:30,550 --> 00:04:33,972
just so that I could start thinking about what type of animation we'd want to do.

75
00:04:33,972 --> 00:04:37,015
We did know at this point we were going to do 3D,

76
00:04:37,015 --> 00:04:38,876
but that's all that we knew.

77
00:04:38,876 --> 00:04:44,922
Lee Petty, who I mentioned before,

78
00:04:44,922 --> 00:04:45,702
he and I were...

79
00:04:46,153 --> 00:04:49,855
taking our lunch breaks and we were going into one of the back rooms and we were doing

80
00:04:49,855 --> 00:04:54,777
just some drawing sessions. And for a couple of those sessions we were focusing on sort

81
00:04:54,777 --> 00:05:00,999
of a mid-century modern style, a very somewhat limited but really beautiful designs. UPA,

82
00:05:00,999 --> 00:05:06,941
which you may have heard of, is one of the studios that's known for that. And then

83
00:05:08,062 --> 00:05:11,924
I was also really interested in Charlie Harper at the time,

84
00:05:11,924 --> 00:05:13,465
the late illustrator Charlie Harper.

85
00:05:13,465 --> 00:05:15,807
I thought his silhouettes were really bold,

86
00:05:15,807 --> 00:05:18,168
he had a really graphic style, but also very expressive.

87
00:05:18,168 --> 00:05:22,931
And I thought it could actually work

88
00:05:22,931 --> 00:05:26,413
if we ended up going with Nathan's style,

89
00:05:26,413 --> 00:05:27,354
which is very painterly.

90
00:05:27,354 --> 00:05:29,796
I thought it would work with those backgrounds.

91
00:05:29,796 --> 00:05:35,619
Then I decided to start doing some animation research,

92
00:05:35,619 --> 00:05:36,420
started looking at the old...

93
00:05:37,981 --> 00:05:39,302
LucasArts adventure games.

94
00:05:39,302 --> 00:05:46,485
When I started looking at those, I realized though that they were extremely limited back

95
00:05:46,485 --> 00:05:46,845
then.

96
00:05:46,845 --> 00:05:51,527
Really beautiful in their own way, but most of the animation was probably about five frames

97
00:05:51,527 --> 00:05:52,107
per second.

98
00:05:52,107 --> 00:05:56,709
I knew that we wanted to have more fidelity than that for this game.

99
00:05:56,709 --> 00:06:05,593
So at the time I was playing Year Walk, as well as Machinarium.

100
00:06:07,261 --> 00:06:18,410
And I really appreciated the level of puppetry that those games had, but I didn't want it

101
00:06:18,410 --> 00:06:20,092
to feel like paper cutouts.

102
00:06:24,923 --> 00:06:28,625
Rayman Origins came out around the time that we were starting to develop our pipeline.

103
00:06:28,625 --> 00:06:31,787
I knew that we didn't need it to be that fleshy.

104
00:06:31,787 --> 00:06:32,948
This was an adventure game.

105
00:06:32,948 --> 00:06:34,429
It wasn't a platformer.

106
00:06:34,429 --> 00:06:37,170
We didn't need to have that much squash and stretch, but we took a lot of inspiration

107
00:06:37,170 --> 00:06:39,051
from the game and from the UB art pipeline.

108
00:06:39,051 --> 00:06:44,774
One of their animators and art directors actually did a talk at GDC a couple years back, which

109
00:06:44,774 --> 00:06:48,056
was very inspirational in what we did.

110
00:06:48,056 --> 00:06:49,477
I also looked at...

111
00:06:50,104 --> 00:06:52,926
shadow puppetry. I didn't...

112
00:06:52,926 --> 00:06:55,808
I knew we wouldn't want something as stiff as that,

113
00:06:55,808 --> 00:06:58,671
but definitely took some inspiration from it.

114
00:06:58,671 --> 00:07:00,292
Eventually I went to Tim, and I said,

115
00:07:00,292 --> 00:07:06,077
Tim, well, what do you want to see in this game?

116
00:07:06,077 --> 00:07:08,319
And, you know, I wanted to get his thoughts.

117
00:07:08,319 --> 00:07:10,181
And his thoughts were,

118
00:07:10,181 --> 00:07:11,742
do something cool.

119
00:07:11,742 --> 00:07:13,203
That's what he told me.

120
00:07:13,203 --> 00:07:18,628
And my response, which is typical, is...

121
00:07:20,333 --> 00:07:23,476
throwing an angry furrow in his direction.

122
00:07:23,476 --> 00:07:26,719
But eventually I realized

123
00:07:26,719 --> 00:07:30,182
that was the best advice that he could give me.

124
00:07:30,182 --> 00:07:33,365
He gave me the opportunity to explore creatively

125
00:07:33,365 --> 00:07:33,946
without boxing me in.

126
00:07:33,946 --> 00:07:35,387
And so I really appreciated that.

127
00:07:35,387 --> 00:07:39,931
So our discoveries.

128
00:07:39,931 --> 00:07:42,133
The art styles had expanded quite a bit.

129
00:07:42,133 --> 00:07:45,756
I knew we'd need lots of expression and fidelity in this game.

130
00:07:46,699 --> 00:07:48,701
We wanted to show off bold silhouettes.

131
00:07:48,701 --> 00:07:51,222
It would not be a 3D game,

132
00:07:51,222 --> 00:07:55,105
so each view had to have a very nice, bold silhouette.

133
00:07:55,105 --> 00:07:59,688
It needed to be compatible with many of our current tools

134
00:07:59,688 --> 00:08:02,430
that included modeling, animation, and rigging,

135
00:08:02,430 --> 00:08:03,671
as well as implementation.

136
00:08:03,671 --> 00:08:05,272
We didn't have the budget or the time

137
00:08:05,272 --> 00:08:07,734
to build an entire new suite of tools.

138
00:08:07,734 --> 00:08:14,298
We knew we were gonna go with 2D planes.

139
00:08:17,318 --> 00:08:19,860
And then we're going to use alpha channels for the soft edges

140
00:08:19,860 --> 00:08:22,642
because we wanted to preserve that look of Nathan's painting style.

141
00:08:22,642 --> 00:08:29,087
And after talking to the programmers, it was decided

142
00:08:29,087 --> 00:08:32,089
we should use a runtime joint-driven system.

143
00:08:32,089 --> 00:08:37,013
We would get huge memory savings, a much smaller memory footprint.

144
00:08:37,013 --> 00:08:39,334
It would also give us the fidelity that we wanted,

145
00:08:39,334 --> 00:08:42,397
knowing that we were going to get lots of dialogue

146
00:08:42,397 --> 00:08:43,558
that we would be animating to.

147
00:08:43,558 --> 00:08:46,220
So, my advice, listen to the programmers.

148
00:08:46,559 --> 00:08:49,421
They are probably better at math than you are.

149
00:08:49,421 --> 00:08:50,842
They have the numbers to back it up.

150
00:08:50,842 --> 00:08:56,084
And we would introduce a new system called flipbook animation.

151
00:08:56,084 --> 00:08:58,466
And all that is, it's pretty simple.

152
00:08:58,466 --> 00:09:04,069
It's keyable texture planes that you can just turn the visibility on and off.

153
00:09:06,754 --> 00:09:08,895
So we'd go with a hybrid approach, which we called 2.5D.

154
00:09:08,895 --> 00:09:12,197
That can mean different things at different studios,

155
00:09:12,197 --> 00:09:14,718
but what it meant at our studio was

156
00:09:14,718 --> 00:09:17,199
flat layer texture planes with transparency,

157
00:09:17,199 --> 00:09:20,401
and they're bound to joint chains,

158
00:09:20,401 --> 00:09:23,202
and each piece of geometry could be turned on and off,

159
00:09:23,202 --> 00:09:25,023
the visibility could be turned on and off.

160
00:09:25,023 --> 00:09:30,786
Next we needed to decide how many views we would need

161
00:09:30,786 --> 00:09:33,287
for each character to get the desired fidelity.

162
00:09:36,333 --> 00:09:37,914
So this was an early test.

163
00:09:37,914 --> 00:09:40,596
When Tim did the Kickstarter, he didn't have a story,

164
00:09:40,596 --> 00:09:44,079
he didn't have a design, he didn't have any treatment.

165
00:09:44,079 --> 00:09:49,383
He wanted the backers to experience

166
00:09:49,383 --> 00:09:51,385
building a game from the very beginning,

167
00:09:51,385 --> 00:09:52,606
even before there was an idea.

168
00:09:52,606 --> 00:09:55,588
And so we couldn't just sit idle as a team,

169
00:09:55,588 --> 00:09:58,231
and so we came up with this scenario,

170
00:09:58,231 --> 00:10:00,232
which we called the Hipster Lumberjack.

171
00:10:00,846 --> 00:10:03,428
And the hipster lumberjack actually ended up in the game

172
00:10:03,428 --> 00:10:05,169
because the backers loved him so much.

173
00:10:05,169 --> 00:10:06,891
He went through a little bit of an evolution.

174
00:10:06,891 --> 00:10:09,453
But this was sort of the first prototype version

175
00:10:09,453 --> 00:10:10,493
of hipster lumberjack.

176
00:10:10,493 --> 00:10:13,276
It's the first model that we built out,

177
00:10:13,276 --> 00:10:15,958
and it's the first rig.

178
00:10:15,958 --> 00:10:17,279
Initially, we thought we were going

179
00:10:17,279 --> 00:10:19,480
to need to do three separate rigs for every view.

180
00:10:20,097 --> 00:10:23,199
But ultimately, with this test, we proved,

181
00:10:23,199 --> 00:10:25,700
okay, we can get away with just one rig,

182
00:10:25,700 --> 00:10:27,481
and we would just put all the views,

183
00:10:27,481 --> 00:10:30,723
we'd put the front, the side, and the back views

184
00:10:30,723 --> 00:10:31,883
all on the same rig.

185
00:10:31,883 --> 00:10:33,985
So you can see here, I did this really simple walk,

186
00:10:33,985 --> 00:10:37,907
and then I'm just turning the views on and off,

187
00:10:37,907 --> 00:10:40,168
each different view, and I did very little changes

188
00:10:40,168 --> 00:10:42,169
to the actual animation.

189
00:10:42,169 --> 00:10:45,591
You can see it's a little janky on the ankles and stuff,

190
00:10:45,591 --> 00:10:47,612
but it did prove out that we could do it.

191
00:10:50,238 --> 00:10:56,840
So, really quickly, so what we have here, I decided, okay, well, I see that we can have

192
00:10:56,840 --> 00:11:00,901
a front, side, and back, but how are these going to all work together?

193
00:11:00,901 --> 00:11:05,702
Or would we be able to overlap the flipbooks?

194
00:11:05,702 --> 00:11:11,343
And so I did, okay, let's do a turn, a 180 turn, because the head leads, and then the

195
00:11:11,343 --> 00:11:14,864
body comes along, and then the legs come along after that.

196
00:11:16,213 --> 00:11:20,116
And so there's actually very little joint animation here.

197
00:11:20,116 --> 00:11:24,439
It's almost all just flip books turning on and off.

198
00:11:24,439 --> 00:11:30,965
You'll notice though that the arm travels across the body

199
00:11:30,965 --> 00:11:33,086
and then just before it gets to the back view,

200
00:11:33,086 --> 00:11:36,229
it pops back into the position that it was in before.

201
00:11:36,229 --> 00:11:39,711
Here it is, it's a little bit slower.

202
00:11:42,440 --> 00:11:51,904
And so the character is in the same view, is in the same pose, front and back, it's just the flip books are turning on and off.

203
00:11:51,904 --> 00:11:57,527
Next, we decided, okay, we're going to have a lot of dialogue, let's do a quick dialogue test.

204
00:11:57,527 --> 00:12:05,710
So, I don't know if you know who Chris Remo is, you might know him from Idle Thumbs, the podcast, he was nice enough to do some scratch dialogue for us.

205
00:12:05,710 --> 00:12:06,471
And we ran this test.

206
00:12:06,471 --> 00:12:09,932
With no sound.

207
00:12:09,932 --> 00:12:12,073
That's interesting.

208
00:12:12,943 --> 00:12:16,285
Well, it gets the point across.

209
00:12:16,285 --> 00:12:18,605
That's just flipbook mouth with

210
00:12:18,605 --> 00:12:24,867
joint driven. Everything else is joint driven except for the mouth

211
00:12:24,867 --> 00:12:28,749
is all flipbooks. Hopefully we have sound for the other

212
00:12:28,749 --> 00:12:33,090
slides, I hope, when we get into the cutscenes.

213
00:12:33,090 --> 00:12:36,731
Okay, so front, side, and back view.

214
00:12:36,731 --> 00:12:40,593
You'll notice though that we didn't do straight on views. We didn't do

215
00:12:41,384 --> 00:12:44,787
We didn't do a totally front-facing face,

216
00:12:44,787 --> 00:12:47,949
or a totally profile face, or a total straight back view.

217
00:12:47,949 --> 00:12:53,393
And we did that because we didn't want the characters to flatten out against the backgrounds,

218
00:12:53,393 --> 00:12:55,274
and so it just kept some dimensionality on them.

219
00:12:55,274 --> 00:13:01,579
Alright, modeling a character with this system.

220
00:13:01,579 --> 00:13:03,040
Super simple.

221
00:13:03,886 --> 00:13:06,427
would take just a few hours to model a character out.

222
00:13:06,427 --> 00:13:09,749
So what the 2D artists would do is they would create

223
00:13:09,749 --> 00:13:12,611
a character and any piece of the character

224
00:13:12,611 --> 00:13:15,633
that needed to be on its own plane,

225
00:13:15,633 --> 00:13:16,653
they would just break out.

226
00:13:16,653 --> 00:13:19,415
And so it was this exploded view.

227
00:13:19,415 --> 00:13:21,136
And we would take that exploded view

228
00:13:21,136 --> 00:13:22,977
and we would just bring it into Maya

229
00:13:22,977 --> 00:13:24,958
and we would build planes around that view.

230
00:13:24,958 --> 00:13:27,039
And then we would just UV map.

231
00:13:29,025 --> 00:13:31,306
the textures onto those planes.

232
00:13:31,306 --> 00:13:32,767
So it's very simple.

233
00:13:32,767 --> 00:13:35,909
Most of the work was in all the painting,

234
00:13:35,909 --> 00:13:38,670
but actually building the model didn't take very long.

235
00:13:38,670 --> 00:13:40,591
Let's do a little bit of a closeup

236
00:13:40,591 --> 00:13:45,433
on how we did the eyes and the face.

237
00:13:45,433 --> 00:13:49,535
If you look, we just did proper edge loops around the eyes

238
00:13:49,535 --> 00:13:51,376
because we knew we wanted to have

239
00:13:51,376 --> 00:13:52,296
a lot of expression in the eyes.

240
00:13:52,296 --> 00:13:55,018
All we were gonna have was eyes and mouth

241
00:13:55,018 --> 00:13:57,339
for facial expression, really.

242
00:13:57,339 --> 00:13:57,819
And so we...

243
00:13:58,827 --> 00:14:03,930
we made sure to do proper edges, just like if you did a 3D model.

244
00:14:03,930 --> 00:14:07,291
You'll look here.

245
00:14:07,291 --> 00:14:10,693
We cut a hole in the eye socket, and the reason for that is

246
00:14:10,693 --> 00:14:14,316
