00:26:47,470 --> 00:26:48,790
when he was doing his nod,

497
00:26:48,790 --> 00:26:53,192
this is... it looks pretty three-dimensional.

498
00:26:53,192 --> 00:26:54,872
But all we're doing actually is just...

499
00:26:55,290 --> 00:27:01,511
deforming the geometry with joints up and down, and it gives it that illusion that his head is actually

500
00:27:01,511 --> 00:27:05,673
nodding up and down. I just thought that was an interesting thing that I'd point out. This is a side note.

501
00:27:05,673 --> 00:27:07,693
Okay, so

502
00:27:07,693 --> 00:27:11,054
this is the cutscene editor.

503
00:27:11,054 --> 00:27:16,236
It's a custom-built tool that we have used

504
00:27:16,236 --> 00:27:21,077
since Psychonauts, actually, and Tim's Games

505
00:27:22,722 --> 00:27:25,404
have outrageous amounts of dialogue.

506
00:27:25,404 --> 00:27:29,448
This game actually had five hours.

507
00:27:29,448 --> 00:27:32,190
With Act 1 and 2, we're looking at five hours

508
00:27:32,190 --> 00:27:33,050
of scripted cut scenes.

509
00:27:33,050 --> 00:27:37,254
And those were all generated by one animator.

510
00:27:37,254 --> 00:27:40,356
So it's a pretty effective system,

511
00:27:40,356 --> 00:27:43,879
as long as you have the canned animation to work with.

512
00:27:43,879 --> 00:27:46,741
You can see that it has the characters who are in the scene.

513
00:27:46,741 --> 00:27:50,084
You have the girl, which is Vela, and then the tram priener.

514
00:27:50,680 --> 00:27:53,743
and then it has the dialogue in there,

515
00:27:53,743 --> 00:27:57,907
it has the animation, each animation is in there

516
00:27:57,907 --> 00:27:59,109
that it's going to use.

517
00:27:59,109 --> 00:28:01,491
The cameras are actually not Maya cameras,

518
00:28:01,491 --> 00:28:02,792
you can see there's a camera track.

519
00:28:02,792 --> 00:28:05,756
Those are cameras that were set up in the game,

520
00:28:05,756 --> 00:28:08,118
and that the game sees each of those,

521
00:28:08,118 --> 00:28:10,300
and then it moves the camera to where it's supposed to be.

522
00:28:10,839 --> 00:28:14,121
We weren't allowed to do panning cameras with scripted cutscenes.

523
00:28:14,121 --> 00:28:16,322
You just have to just pop to the different scenes.

524
00:28:16,322 --> 00:28:18,464
So you are limited by what you can do,

525
00:28:18,464 --> 00:28:20,105
but it sure saves a lot of time.

526
00:28:20,105 --> 00:28:21,386
Here's an example.

527
00:28:21,386 --> 00:28:23,907
We use these a lot for dialogue trees, actually,

528
00:28:23,907 --> 00:28:25,568
which Tim's games have a lot of.

529
00:28:25,568 --> 00:28:27,850
We have a sound.

530
00:28:27,850 --> 00:28:28,010
Your name?

531
00:28:28,010 --> 00:28:28,170
Well, yeah.

532
00:28:28,170 --> 00:28:28,430
But my dad said,

533
00:28:28,430 --> 00:28:29,711
hey, losing an A is better than losing an I.

534
00:28:39,777 --> 00:28:41,017
Your dad's pretty funny.

535
00:28:41,017 --> 00:28:44,159
He used to be, before he joined this cult.

536
00:28:44,159 --> 00:28:46,661
Oh, whoops. Did I say that too loud?

537
00:28:46,661 --> 00:28:50,783
Hey, is there any way out of this cloud?

538
00:28:50,783 --> 00:28:52,885
Think I'd be here if there were?

539
00:28:52,885 --> 00:28:59,569
We used to have a cool feather bedder that went straight down to the forest below.

540
00:28:59,569 --> 00:29:01,890
But Harmony took it out.

541
00:29:03,894 --> 00:29:05,215
So it's pretty effective.

542
00:29:05,215 --> 00:29:07,436
I mean, it doesn't have as much fidelity

543
00:29:07,436 --> 00:29:10,739
as a fully animated cutscene might have,

544
00:29:10,739 --> 00:29:12,240
but it definitely does the job.

545
00:29:12,240 --> 00:29:16,983
Okay, if you notice, there was lip sync during all those,

546
00:29:16,983 --> 00:29:21,586
and we did not have the time to animate all the lip sync.

547
00:29:21,586 --> 00:29:22,246
So let's see.

548
00:29:24,337 --> 00:29:29,202
So, Act 2 of Broken Age, we're looking at over 47,000 words.

549
00:29:29,202 --> 00:29:32,525
Most of those would have to get lip-sync.

550
00:29:32,525 --> 00:29:37,710
And we were a pretty small team, and there's no way that we could pull that off by ourselves.

551
00:29:37,710 --> 00:29:43,215
So we use an auto-lip-sync tool, and it's a third-party tool by AnoSoft.

552
00:29:43,827 --> 00:29:45,168
It's very effective.

553
00:29:45,168 --> 00:29:47,890
What we would do for this game is

554
00:29:47,890 --> 00:29:50,551
the 2D artist would give us a visem set.

555
00:29:50,551 --> 00:29:53,033
We would then take that, we would just map it onto a plane

556
00:29:53,033 --> 00:29:56,316
and put it onto the character, bind that to a joint.

557
00:29:56,316 --> 00:29:57,056
We would then use what we have,

558
00:29:57,056 --> 00:30:02,880
this is an internal tool called the animation toolbox.

559
00:30:02,880 --> 00:30:06,923
And what this does is this lets us save poses out

560
00:30:06,923 --> 00:30:08,064
on specific joints.

561
00:30:08,064 --> 00:30:11,767
And in this case, it is a joint and a flip book.

562
00:30:13,034 --> 00:30:16,036
And so those are our phoneme sets that we've set up,

563
00:30:16,036 --> 00:30:19,978
which are just poses that are saved.

564
00:30:19,978 --> 00:30:24,860
We then take those phonemes and we match them up

565
00:30:24,860 --> 00:30:26,421
with the software's phonemes.

566
00:30:26,421 --> 00:30:32,804
If you look, it's like the ah has A-E-ah, ah, A-W, and A-Y.

567
00:30:32,804 --> 00:30:33,805
Then.

568
00:30:35,978 --> 00:30:40,501
We take that and we open up our custom interface that we've built for the software

569
00:30:40,501 --> 00:30:44,223
and you can actually bring in the line codes from the dialog database

570
00:30:44,223 --> 00:30:50,528
and what it does is it looks at the line code and then it looks at the waveform

571
00:30:50,528 --> 00:30:54,430
and it also looks at the text

572
00:30:54,430 --> 00:30:55,911
and it generates a

573
00:30:55,911 --> 00:30:57,552
it generates a Maya file

574
00:30:57,552 --> 00:31:02,536
and that Maya file, you can just actually open it up and make any changes if you need to

575
00:31:02,536 --> 00:31:05,618
but if you open it, all you see is the mouth just moving and talking.

576
00:31:07,294 --> 00:31:09,395
So here's an example of one that an animator hasn't touched.

577
00:31:09,395 --> 00:31:10,075
It's just out of the arcade.

578
00:31:10,075 --> 00:31:11,056
I beat my own high score on 3 Hyper Crit,

579
00:31:11,056 --> 00:31:21,623
and I was like, if I can do that, I can do anything!

580
00:31:21,623 --> 00:31:22,104
Right, so that's Gus.

581
00:31:22,104 --> 00:31:24,305
That's actually voiced by Pendleton Ward from Adventure

582
00:31:24,305 --> 00:31:26,287
Time, if you recognize the voice.

583
00:31:26,697 --> 00:31:29,499
If you want to know any more about our dialogue system,

584
00:31:29,499 --> 00:31:31,600
Anna Kipnis, our lead gameplay programmer,

585
00:31:31,600 --> 00:31:33,481
is giving a talk this Friday.

586
00:31:33,481 --> 00:31:34,302
It's a really good talk.

587
00:31:34,302 --> 00:31:36,183
It's on our entire dialogue system,

588
00:31:36,183 --> 00:31:37,785
what we've been using for years.

589
00:31:37,785 --> 00:31:40,126
So if you have an interest in that, go see that talk.

590
00:31:40,126 --> 00:31:40,366
All right.

591
00:31:40,366 --> 00:31:42,528
Player locomotion.

592
00:31:42,528 --> 00:31:45,130
I'd mentioned stance animation, which

593
00:31:45,130 --> 00:31:46,811
include player locomotion.

594
00:31:46,811 --> 00:31:48,452
Very important in this game.

595
00:31:48,452 --> 00:31:53,035
It's an adventure game, a lot of walking.

596
00:31:53,035 --> 00:31:53,636
Sorry about that.

597
00:31:54,706 --> 00:31:57,328
So we had west and east directions,

598
00:31:57,328 --> 00:32:00,230
and we had northeast and we had southwest.

599
00:32:00,230 --> 00:32:02,551
We had northwest and southeast,

600
00:32:02,551 --> 00:32:04,453
and that's what we were gonna stick with.

601
00:32:04,453 --> 00:32:07,455
We ran some tests and played it a little bit

602
00:32:07,455 --> 00:32:10,037
and realized maybe it was a little annoying

603
00:32:10,037 --> 00:32:12,678
to make people always go at an angle.

604
00:32:12,678 --> 00:32:16,901
And so eventually we added north and south directions.

605
00:32:16,901 --> 00:32:18,703
But every direction that we added,

606
00:32:18,703 --> 00:32:20,524
we needed to author new animation for.

607
00:32:21,020 --> 00:32:25,483
And not only did we need to author one speed of animation,

608
00:32:25,483 --> 00:32:28,925
we ended up having three speeds of animation in the game.

609
00:32:28,925 --> 00:32:30,306
So we had a walk.

610
00:32:30,306 --> 00:32:31,747
I'll show you.

611
00:32:31,747 --> 00:32:32,467
I'll show you an example.

612
00:32:32,467 --> 00:32:34,849
We had a walk, and we had a trot,

613
00:32:34,849 --> 00:32:36,369
and then we also had a run.

614
00:32:36,369 --> 00:32:37,970
And these are for our player characters.

615
00:32:37,970 --> 00:32:39,251
We have two player characters.

616
00:32:39,251 --> 00:32:40,872
We have Vela, and we have Shay.

617
00:32:40,872 --> 00:32:47,576
So there were certain times we wanted to use walks.

618
00:32:47,576 --> 00:32:48,196
So here's an example.

619
00:32:48,196 --> 00:32:50,338
A confined space on the spaceship.

620
00:32:53,475 --> 00:32:54,376
he's walking around.

621
00:32:54,376 --> 00:32:56,637
We would not want the character to be running around in there.

622
00:32:56,637 --> 00:32:58,919
Probably not even want them trotting

623
00:32:58,919 --> 00:33:01,060
because the area is so confined.

624
00:33:01,060 --> 00:33:03,622
And so the programmer could just lock out

625
00:33:03,622 --> 00:33:05,123
the locomotion that they wanted to.

626
00:33:05,123 --> 00:33:07,564
And then to the opposite extreme,

627
00:33:07,564 --> 00:33:09,285
we have big hallways,

628
00:33:09,285 --> 00:33:11,567
which that's when we determined we needed to have some runs.

629
00:33:11,567 --> 00:33:13,888
And so there's Shay running back and forth

630
00:33:13,888 --> 00:33:15,029
because you didn't want the player

631
00:33:15,029 --> 00:33:18,531
to have to every time walk slowly through those corridors.

632
00:33:18,531 --> 00:33:21,613
They would get bored and maybe stop playing your game.

633
00:33:24,657 --> 00:33:27,599
What this shows is just, this is all Vela's anims,

634
00:33:27,599 --> 00:33:31,621
right here, these are all of her walk anims put together.

635
00:33:31,621 --> 00:33:36,043
So we had eight directions, three speeds,

636
00:33:36,043 --> 00:33:39,025
and we needed to author 15 separate animations

637
00:33:39,025 --> 00:33:42,067
for locomotion for the player character,

638
00:33:42,067 --> 00:33:43,487
for her and then for Shay.

639
00:33:43,487 --> 00:33:45,669
And then for north and north, or sorry,

640
00:33:45,669 --> 00:33:47,870
west and northwest and southwest,

641
00:33:47,870 --> 00:33:50,731
we could just actually mirror them in the game engine,

642
00:33:50,731 --> 00:33:52,292
so we didn't have to author those.

643
00:34:28,200 --> 00:34:30,181
All right.

644
00:34:30,181 --> 00:34:34,625
Perspective scaling, that's perspective scaling to the extreme.

645
00:34:34,625 --> 00:34:40,791
It was something that was very important in Broken Age.

646
00:34:40,791 --> 00:34:44,134
So as the character goes back in the distance,

647
00:34:45,079 --> 00:34:49,860
they scale down and it appears that they actually are moving much more slowly.

648
00:34:49,860 --> 00:34:53,741
And that was really important in this game because we didn't actually have real depth.

649
00:34:53,741 --> 00:34:57,101
We were faking it. We were faking it by scaling the character down,

650
00:34:57,101 --> 00:34:58,922
but not only scaling the character down,

651
00:34:58,922 --> 00:35:01,662
we need to scale the speed down of the character as well.

652
00:35:01,662 --> 00:35:05,783
So, let me show you an example of

653
00:35:05,783 --> 00:35:10,604
the game with perspective scaling on.

654
00:35:11,573 --> 00:35:14,975
but perspective, but root scaling not turned on.

655
00:35:14,975 --> 00:35:17,176
You can see how quickly she moves.

656
00:35:17,176 --> 00:35:20,218
So she's actually moving at the authored speed

657
00:35:20,218 --> 00:35:22,159
that the animator authored her at.

658
00:35:22,159 --> 00:35:26,862
But when she scales down,

659
00:35:26,862 --> 00:35:29,724
it looks like it appears that she's moving much faster.

660
00:35:29,724 --> 00:35:35,548
And so the solution is root motion scaling.

661
00:35:35,548 --> 00:35:37,209
So you'll see here.

662
00:35:40,298 --> 00:35:44,442
This is feeling much better than it did before.

663
00:35:44,442 --> 00:35:48,406
Feels like she's set back in perspective.

664
00:35:48,406 --> 00:35:53,010
But I wasn't 100% convinced by it.

665
00:35:53,010 --> 00:35:59,436
I thought that it could be improved, and so I started doing some tests.

666
00:35:59,436 --> 00:36:00,037
I did this test.

667
00:36:01,135 --> 00:36:06,239
of Vela, just in Maya, this is on one of the scenes on the beach,

668
00:36:06,239 --> 00:36:08,341
of Vela walking on the beach.

669
00:36:08,341 --> 00:36:12,545
And so I had felt that before the spacing was wrong

670
00:36:12,545 --> 00:36:15,047
when she was back in the distance.

671
00:36:15,047 --> 00:36:19,371
And so I ran this test and I got it looking to where I was pretty happy with it,

672
00:36:19,371 --> 00:36:25,077
and then I took it over to, I showed it to Anna Kipnis, who is our lead gameplay programmer,

673
00:36:25,077 --> 00:36:26,178
and I also sent her...

674
00:36:26,833 --> 00:36:31,054
images of the curves so that she could see how the curves were.

675
00:36:31,054 --> 00:36:33,795
You know, it's sort of very gradual and then it speeds up.

676
00:36:33,795 --> 00:36:35,916
And then not only that, in this game,

677
00:36:35,916 --> 00:36:40,878
this is the curve of the scale of Vela.

678
00:36:40,878 --> 00:36:45,200
And so we had a global scale node that would allow the animators

679
00:36:45,200 --> 00:36:49,321
to scale the entire character up or down

680
00:36:49,321 --> 00:36:54,163
because we were using perspective scaling and forced perspective.

681
00:36:56,842 --> 00:37:01,484
So here it is. It's a little subtle, but I think you'll see the difference.

682
00:37:01,484 --> 00:37:08,126
This is it with the new perspective, the root scaling that Anna set up.

683
00:37:08,126 --> 00:37:22,271
I just felt like it gave it much more depth than it did before.

684
00:37:28,926 --> 00:37:30,526
Okay.

685
00:37:30,526 --> 00:37:33,547
So, we're getting near the shipping,

686
00:37:33,547 --> 00:37:35,308
the first act of Broken Age.

687
00:37:35,308 --> 00:37:37,288
We were running the game.

688
00:37:37,288 --> 00:37:38,869
It could run at 60 frames per second.

689
00:37:38,869 --> 00:37:40,469
Cut scenes were running at 30 frames per second

690
00:37:40,469 --> 00:37:41,990
because they were authored in Maya,

691
00:37:41,990 --> 00:37:44,370
but the game could go up to 60 frames per second

692
00:37:44,370 --> 00:37:46,171
during just, when you're just walking around.

693
00:37:46,171 --> 00:37:51,852
And one day I came in and Oliver Fronsky,

694
00:37:51,852 --> 00:37:53,733
he's our lead programmer,

695
00:37:53,733 --> 00:37:56,274
he was messing around with this pixelized,

696
00:37:56,274 --> 00:37:57,714
pixelated version of the game.

697
00:37:59,793 --> 00:38:03,555
And when I saw this, I was pretty intrigued,

698
00:38:03,555 --> 00:38:07,396
and I actually saw a cut scene play,

699
00:38:07,396 --> 00:38:10,697
and I felt like everything felt cohesive suddenly.

700
00:38:10,697 --> 00:38:12,497
And so we started talking about it,

701
00:38:12,497 --> 00:38:15,358
and what we realized is that the flip books

702
00:38:15,358 --> 00:38:18,499
were clashing a little bit with the game,

703
00:38:18,499 --> 00:38:19,640
when it's with the character

704
00:38:19,640 --> 00:38:21,580
and with the joint-driven animation.

705
00:38:22,096 --> 00:38:26,578
because you had one thing just, you know, that was such a stark change

706
00:38:26,578 --> 00:38:30,199
and then you had the joints that were, you know, look like they were being interpolated by the

707
00:38:30,199 --> 00:38:32,360
by the computer at 30 to 60 frames per second.

708
00:38:32,360 --> 00:38:36,202
So this is what it looked like.

709
00:38:36,202 --> 00:38:38,283
This is probably running close to 60 frames per second.

710
00:38:38,283 --> 00:38:44,225
Like it looks cool, looks really smooth

711
00:38:44,225 --> 00:38:46,006
but it doesn't look, um...

712
00:38:47,482 --> 00:38:50,763
very hand done. It doesn't look like hands touched it, I felt.

713
00:38:50,763 --> 00:38:58,746
And so what we did is we re-sampled the animation

714
00:38:58,746 --> 00:39:00,327
down to 15 frames per second.

715
00:39:00,327 --> 00:39:06,749
Can you see the difference?

716
00:39:06,749 --> 00:39:10,210
This ended up working a lot better, I felt, especially in the cut scenes

717
00:39:10,210 --> 00:39:12,691
when the flipbooks would turn on and off.

718
00:39:12,691 --> 00:39:16,052
There wasn't such a stark contrast between the joint-driven

719
00:39:16,699 --> 00:39:22,523
geometry and then the flipbook driven geometry.

720
00:39:22,523 --> 00:39:24,084
So it's a subtle change.

721
00:39:24,084 --> 00:39:26,045
It was actually somewhat controversial.

722
00:39:26,045 --> 00:39:26,986
Some people didn't want to do it

723
00:39:26,986 --> 00:39:28,947
and some of us wanted to do it.

724
00:39:28,947 --> 00:39:32,930
But we ultimately won and we went with this.

725
00:39:32,930 --> 00:39:36,392
So we thought we were golden at this point.

726
00:39:36,392 --> 00:39:41,976
But then we watched one of our cut scenes play,

727
00:39:41,976 --> 00:39:42,776
which is this one.

728
00:39:46,623 --> 00:39:48,044
Let's see what we ended up with.

729
00:39:48,044 --> 00:39:48,164
That.

730
00:39:48,164 --> 00:39:52,987
That's what we ended up with.

731
00:39:52,987 --> 00:39:57,509
And so my hopes were somewhat dashed for a moment

732
00:39:57,509 --> 00:40:00,471
that we weren't going to get to resample to 15 frames

733
00:40:00,471 --> 00:40:02,012
per second because of that.

734
00:40:02,012 --> 00:40:03,433
And what's happening is.

735
00:40:04,578 --> 00:40:08,639
The character's animation is resampled down to 15 frames per second,

736
00:40:08,639 --> 00:40:10,019
but the camera is not.

737
00:40:10,019 --> 00:40:13,340
So the camera is still running, in this case, at 30 frames per second.

738
00:40:13,340 --> 00:40:15,801
This is an old animation problem.

739
00:40:15,801 --> 00:40:19,842
If you had a background plate that was moving on 1s,

740
00:40:19,842 --> 00:40:24,283
but if you had your actual animated character on 2s,

741
00:40:24,283 --> 00:40:26,104
you'd get this horrible strobing effect.

742
00:40:26,104 --> 00:40:32,045
And so what Oliver did is he went in and he set...

743
00:40:33,184 --> 00:40:40,626
he set it up so that the character's root motion would actually move at 30 frames per second

744
00:40:40,626 --> 00:40:46,868
or 60 frames per second, whether it was a cutscene, it was 30, if it was in-game, it was 60.

745
00:40:46,868 --> 00:40:49,288
So the root motion actually would not resample.

746
00:40:49,288 --> 00:40:50,188
And that works.

747
00:40:50,188 --> 00:40:52,389
This is what we get when that happens.

748
00:40:59,228 --> 00:41:01,230
So then it's nice and smooth.

749
00:41:01,230 --> 00:41:05,673
So the character's actually moving at 30,

750
00:41:05,673 --> 00:41:08,615
but all of her limbs and everything

751
00:41:08,615 --> 00:41:10,517
are actually animating at 15 frames per second.

752
00:41:10,517 --> 00:41:15,600
And that was a great solution for us.

753
00:41:15,600 --> 00:41:20,464
Okay, so one of our biggest headaches on this project.

754
00:41:21,270 --> 00:41:22,611
we had no Z depth buffer.

755
00:41:22,611 --> 00:41:25,393
And the reason we didn't have the Z depth buffer is we,

756
00:41:25,393 --> 00:41:27,794
one of the big reasons is we needed the memory

757
00:41:27,794 --> 00:41:32,717
for transparency, we needed it for the transparent textures.

758
00:41:32,717 --> 00:41:35,118
And everything is pretty much a painting in this game,

759
00:41:35,118 --> 00:41:39,040
and we needed as much memory for that as we could have,

760
00:41:39,040 --> 00:41:42,362
and so we chose to drop the Z depth buffer.

761
00:41:42,362 --> 00:41:45,003
That caused a lot of animation bugs,

762
00:41:45,003 --> 00:41:48,225
because the engine didn't know how to sort

763
00:41:49,022 --> 00:41:51,984
all the different planes that we had created,

764
00:41:51,984 --> 00:41:56,868
if you rotated them at all, other than what we call the Z,

765
00:41:56,868 --> 00:41:58,809
which is the Z rotation like this.

766
00:41:58,809 --> 00:42:01,331
If you rotate them at all towards the camera,

767
00:42:01,331 --> 00:42:03,453
everything would just blow up.

768
00:42:03,453 --> 00:42:07,376
We had a couple of animators that were having a hard time with this,

769
00:42:07,376 --> 00:42:07,676
because...

770
00:42:08,692 --> 00:42:12,455
When you're working in Maya, we're actually using a 3D camera,

771
00:42:12,455 --> 00:42:14,596
and you'd turn the camera, and it looked fine.

772
00:42:14,596 --> 00:42:15,997
There wasn't any problem.

773
00:42:15,997 --> 00:42:18,459
You could even turn the head a little bit on the character,

774
00:42:18,459 --> 00:42:19,320
and it would still hold up.

775
00:42:19,320 --> 00:42:20,541
But this is the result that you would get.

776
00:42:20,541 --> 00:42:21,541
OK, that's enough.

777
00:42:21,541 --> 00:42:22,562
What do you mean, that's enough?

778
00:42:22,562 --> 00:42:23,282
