780
00:42:24,003 --> 00:42:28,366
I need to save this last one.

781
00:42:28,366 --> 00:42:37,212
You're going to endanger the whole mission to save one creature?

782
00:42:37,212 --> 00:42:37,953
Just give me a second.

783
00:42:40,377 --> 00:42:43,699
So you can see, we ended up with lots of bugs.

784
00:42:43,699 --> 00:42:45,880
Most of our bugs in the first act

785
00:42:45,880 --> 00:42:49,901
was because animators thought that they could rotate things

786
00:42:49,901 --> 00:42:51,662
however they wanted to.

787
00:42:51,662 --> 00:42:54,664
But that's the result that you would get.

788
00:42:54,664 --> 00:42:59,046
Even just a little bit, it would just explode like that.

789
00:43:01,057 --> 00:43:05,240
If you want to know a little bit more about that, Oliver Fronsky, his website, he actually

790
00:43:05,240 --> 00:43:09,623
has some papers about it, and you can go and find out more technical details about that

791
00:43:09,623 --> 00:43:10,283
system.

792
00:43:10,283 --> 00:43:14,566
You might find that interesting if you're a TD or a programmer.

793
00:43:14,566 --> 00:43:19,510
Okay, so what we learned from this hybrid approach...

794
00:43:21,690 --> 00:43:24,552
to mold your pipeline to your current tool set.

795
00:43:24,552 --> 00:43:26,353
We found that that was very important.

796
00:43:26,353 --> 00:43:27,493
We knew how to use our tools.

797
00:43:27,493 --> 00:43:30,275
Our animators knew how to use the tools.

798
00:43:30,275 --> 00:43:33,717
And so why start over if you don't have to?

799
00:43:33,717 --> 00:43:35,438
We got huge performance advantages

800
00:43:35,438 --> 00:43:40,560
from using joint deformation versus sprite sheets.

801
00:43:40,560 --> 00:43:43,742
It was a really easy ramp up for 3D animators,

802
00:43:43,742 --> 00:43:45,963
except for the rotating the limbs

803
00:43:45,963 --> 00:43:47,604
the way they weren't supposed to.

804
00:43:47,604 --> 00:43:48,925
That was the only exception to that.

805
00:43:50,027 --> 00:43:58,572
Joint-driven deformation, it really allowed the fidelity that we wanted in this game and that made Tim happy.

806
00:43:58,572 --> 00:44:02,454
The 15 frames per second, we felt that that blended really well with the flipbooks.

807
00:44:02,454 --> 00:44:06,196
It was kind of a last-minute decision, but we went for it, and I'm glad that we did.

808
00:44:06,196 --> 00:44:12,540
The scripted cutscenes, it will save thousands of animation hours.

809
00:44:12,540 --> 00:44:17,663
It truly did save us, and it's what allowed us to make this game and to complete this game.

810
00:44:18,590 --> 00:44:25,754
